= Chapter Concepts
- Climate is the major determinant of plant growth form and distribution.
- Climate defines the boundaries of terrestrial biomes.
- Walter climate diagrams distinguish the major terrestrial biomes.
- Temperate climate zones have average annual temperatures between 5°C and 20°C.
- Boreal and polar climate zones have average temperatures below 5°C.
- Climate zones within tropical latitudes have average temperatures exceeding 20°C.
- The biome concept must be modified for freshwater aquatic systems.
- Marine aquatic systems are classified principally by water depth.

= Introduction to Biomes
== Convergence and Growth Forms
- Convergence: Unrelated organisms evolve similar forms in response to similar environmental conditions.
- Example: Cactus (Cactaceae) and euphorb (Euphorbiaceae) trees in arid environments.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.1").path, width: 50%),
)
- Growth form is closely matched to environment; physical structure determines water demand and tolerance.

== Biome Classification
- Biomes are categories of biological communities and ecosystems based on climate and dominant plant form.
- Major biomes in North America: tundra, boreal forest, temperate seasonal forest, temperate rain forest, shrubland, grassland, subtropical desert.
- Biome boundaries correspond to climate zones; classification systems may vary in detail.

= Climate and Biome Distribution
== Climate as a Determinant
- Climate (temperature and precipitation) determines plant growth form and distribution.
- Adaptations in leaves and spacing reflect biome conditions (e.g., broad leaves in temperate forests, small leaves in deserts).
- Example: Sugar maple distribution limited by cold, heat, and drought.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.2").path, width: 50%),
)
- Related species (black, red, silver maples) differ in ecological tolerances and soil preferences.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.3").path, width: 50%),
)

== Climate Zone Classification
- Heinrich Walter's system: Nine climate zones based on annual temperature and precipitation cycles.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.4").path, width: 50%),
)
- Robert Whittaker's system: Biomes defined by vegetation type, plotted against temperature and precipitation.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.5").path, width: 50%),
)
- Fire influences biome boundaries, especially in grasslands and shrublands.

== Walter Climate Diagrams
- Walter climate diagrams show seasonal periods of water deficit and abundance.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.6").path, width: 50%),
)
- Each climate zone has a typical seasonal pattern of temperature and precipitation.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.7").path, width: 50%),
)
- Global distribution of biomes follows temperature and precipitation patterns.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.8").path, width: 50%),
)

= Major Terrestrial Biomes
== Temperate Seasonal Forest (Nemoral, VI)
- Moderate conditions with winter freezing; dominant in eastern US, southeastern Canada, Europe, eastern Asia.
- Deciduous trees, layered vegetation, podsolized soils.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.9").path, width: 50%),
)

== Temperate Rain Forest (Warm Temperate, V)
- Mild winters, heavy winter rains, summer fog; supports tall evergreen forests (redwood, Douglas-fir).
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.10").path, width: 50%),
)

== Temperate Grassland/Desert (Continental, VII)
- Grasslands (prairies, steppes) with 30–85 cm rainfall, cold winters, rich mollisol soils.
- Fire-resistant species, grazing pressure, conversion to desert by overgrazing.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.11").path, width: 50%),
)

== Woodland/Shrubland (Mediterranean, IV)
- Mild winters, winter rain, summer drought; sclerophyllous vegetation, frequent fires.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.12").path, width: 50%),
)

== Subtropical Desert (Hot Deserts, III)
- Sparse rainfall (<25 cm), high temperatures, long growing seasons, aridosol soils.
- Succulent cacti, shrubs, small trees; high species diversity.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.13").path, width: 50%),
)

== Boreal Forest (Taiga, VIII)
- Broad belt at high latitudes; evergreen needle-leaved trees, moist soils, acidic podsolized soils, low diversity.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.14").path, width: 50%),
)

== Tundra (Polar, IX)
- Treeless expanse, permafrost, acidic soils, dwarf shrubs, harsh winters, short growing season.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.15").path, width: 50%),
)

== Tropical Rain Forest (Equatorial, I)
- Always warm, >200 cm precipitation, continuous canopy, high productivity and diversity, rapid nutrient cycling.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.16").path, width: 50%),
)

== Tropical Seasonal Forest/Savanna (Tropical, II)
- Pronounced dry season, deciduous trees, savannas with scattered trees, fire and grazing maintain character.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.17").path, width: 50%),
)

= Aquatic Biomes
== Freshwater Systems
- Biome concept modified for aquatic systems; classified by physical factors (depth, flow, nutrients).
- Streams and rivers (lotic systems): riffles and pools, river continuum concept, allochthonous vs. autochthonous inputs.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.18").path, width: 50%),
)
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.19").path, width: 50%),
)
- Lakes and ponds (lentic systems): littoral, limnetic, benthic zones.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.20").path, width: 50%),
)
- Wetlands: saturated soils, unique plants, ecosystem functions (pollutant removal).

== Estuaries
- Mix of fresh and salt water, high productivity, bordered by tidal marshes and mangrove wetlands.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.21").path, width: 50%),
)

== Marine Systems
- Classified by water depth: littoral (intertidal), neritic (continental shelf), oceanic (deep sea), benthic (seafloor).
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.22").path, width: 50%),
)
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.23").path, width: 50%),
)
- Coral reefs: high productivity and diversity, symbiosis with algae, vulnerable to bleaching.
#figure(
  image(images.at("5.24").path, width: 50%),
)

= Summary of Key Points
- Geographic distributions of plants are determined primarily by climate.
- Plant growth form matches temperature and precipitation; biomes classified by vegetation type.
- Climate zones and biomes grouped by latitude: tropical, temperate, boreal, polar.
- Major temperate biomes: temperate seasonal forest, temperate rain forest, temperate grassland/desert, woodland/shrubland, subtropical desert.
- Boreal forest and tundra at high latitudes; tropical rain forest and seasonal forest/savanna at low latitudes.
- Aquatic systems classified by physical factors; river continuum concept, ecological zones in lakes, wetlands, estuaries, marine depth zones.
